# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-phosphaallenes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] DBU can be synthesised in three steps from caprolactam and acrylonitrile.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] First, the nitrile undergoes an addition reaction at the caprolactam nitrogen, producing *N*-(2-cyanoethyl)-caprolactam.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] This is then hydrogenated to *N*-aminopropyl-caprolactam, followed by an intramolecular carbonyl condensation to form the imine.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] Water is removed by fractional distillation.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] Although all commercially available DBU is produced synthetically, it may also be isolated from the sea sponge *Niphates digitalis*.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-8-diazabicyclo-5-4-0-undec-7-ene] The biosynthesis of DBU has been proposed to begin with adipaldehyde and 1,3-diaminopropane.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The first example of a stable heteroalkene E=C or E=E' (E, E' = P) containing a heavy group 15 element was reported in 1982 by Yoshifuji.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] After the realization of heavier heteroalkenes, the field of organometallic chemistry began exploring the idea of heteroallenes E=C=E' and E=C=C=E', in which one or more carbon atom of an allene is substituted by a heavier atom.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The first of these heteroallenes containing a heavier group 15 element to be reported was synthesized in 1984 by Yoshifuji.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] 1-phosphaallene, also referred to as ethenylidenephosphine or λ3-phosphaallene, was first synthesized using the 2,4,6-tri-t-butylphenyl (supermesityl, or Mes*) moiety as a sterically protecting group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The most widely known example of 1-phosphaalenes is the Mes* substituted 3H-phosphallene, where a hydrogen is bonded to the terminal carbon atom, which was synthesized by Märkl and Reitinger in 1988.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Some more recent advances made in regards to 1-phosphaallenes include the development of simpler synthetic routes and the discovery of synthetic pathways using phosphaallenes to create molecules that are typically only synthesized through complicated methods.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple synthetic routes to 1-phosphaallenes have been reported.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The most common are Phospha-Wittig-Horner reactions, rearrangement of alkylynlphosphines with a base present, dehydrochlorination of a chlorovinylphospine, and the reaction of lithium with a C,C-dichlorophosphirane.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] More recent synthetic advances include the dehydrobromination of phosphaalkenes the hydroalumination of alkynylphosphines.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The Phospha-Wittig-Horner reaction, first reported by Mathey et al. in 1992, was initially developed as a synthetic route to convert aldehydes and ketones into C-mono and C,C-disubstituted phosphaalkenes, respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] This method was then adapted to rapidly synthesize phosphaallenes by reacting phosphaketenes with an organolithium base, such as lithium diisopropylamide or t-BuOLi.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] n-BuLi is used as a strong base in the synthesis of a phosphaallene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] A lithium complex can be used to synthesize phosphaallenes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Like the transition from an alkyne to an allene in organic chemistry, phosphaallenes can be synthesized from alkynylphosphines by adding a strong base such as n-butyllithium (n-BuLi).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] These complexes are typically useful due to the broad range of stable products that can be obtained from this synthetic route.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple stable phosphaallenes have been synthesized from LiC≡CR and ArP(H)Cl (R = Ph, t-Bu, Me, CH2OSiMe3).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The basicity of the lithium complex is essential to the success of these reactions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The dehydrochlorination of 1-chlorovinylphosphine by DBU (1,8-diazabicyclo-[5.4.0]undec-7-ene) yields a variety of results, depending on the structure of the initial chlorovinylphosphine.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Many of these reactions require temperatures between −90 °C and 0 °C to ensure a stable product is formed.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] As many of these reactions are warmed, oligomerization of the phosphaallene occurs.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Other reactions following this synthetic route occur with gas phase reagents at 250 °C.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In this synthetic route, a dichlorocarbene is first reacted with a phosphaethylene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The addition of t-BuLi to the resulting 2,2-dichlorophosphirane yields the phosphaallene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] This route includes an insertion of carbon into the P=C bond of a phosphaalkene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene with the sterically cumbersome Mes* moiety was reacted with t-BuOK to yield the cyclopropylidenephosphaethene product.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Treatment of the (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene reagent with a weaker base, EtONa yields a non-cyclic isomer that can undergo cyclization in the presence of t-BuOK.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In 2019, a new synthetic route for the synthesis of phosphaallenes was reported by Klöcker and coworkers.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroalumination of dialkynylphosphines with different alkylaluminium hydrides resulted in the elimination of dialkylaluminium alkynides and the desired phosphaallenes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Many of the phosphaallenes Klöcker and coworkers synthesized spontaneously decomposed into less-desired products, but the newly reported synthetic method did allow for the isolation of some highly reactive compounds that had not been isolated previously.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In 2022, the most notable aspect of 1-phosphaallenes is their reactivity.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes contain three reactive centers: the P=C bond, the C=C bond, and the phosphorus atom.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The P=C bond and the C=C bond are thought to be electronically independent of one another.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] This gives rise to a wide variety of reactivity, which is similar to that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Without a large steric hindrance, most phosphaallenes quickly dimerize in a [2+2]- or [2+3]-cycloaddition to yield four- or five-membered rings.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Thus, in order to prevent dimerization, a bulky moiety such as Mes* is often used.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Dimerization frequently occurs in a head-to-tail manner, exhibiting coupling between either the two C=C bonds or the two P=C bonds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The regioselectivity of these dimerization reactions depends on the substituents on the C in the 3 position.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Nucleophilic alkoxide as well as n-BuLi will add to the P=C bond of a phosphaallene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] As seen in the reaction scheme, the central C atom is the preferred location for proton attack due to the partial negative charge it possesses.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The reaction of phosphaallenes with dichlorocarbenes results in a [2+1]-cycloaddition to the P=C double bond, which results in stable heterocyclic compounds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes have also been investigated as reagents to form carbenes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Reacting the phosphaallene H2P=C=PH with acetylene yields a carbene via [3 + 2]-cycloaddition.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Crystal structure showing phosphaallene-transition metal coordination.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes can coordinate in an ɳ1 or ɳ2 fashion depending on the metal and experimental conditions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Recent studies into the coordination behavior of the 3H-phosphaallene with tungsten (W) show that both stable and unstable phosphaallenes can bond to W through and ɳ1-coordination mode via a P-W bond.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Due to the stabilizing effect of coordination, reacting transient phosphaallenes with W has become a common method to create stable phosphaallenes that can then be characterized.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] These studies have also demonstrated that 3H-phosphaallenes exhibit ɳ2-coordination to Pt via side-on overlap between Pt and the P=C double bond resulting in a three-membered PtPC heterocycle.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Head-to-tail dimerization of 3H-phosphaallene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Tricyclic phosphine resulting from decomposition via irradiation.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Decomposition of the 3H-phosphaallene occurs at room-temperature to produce several products via P=C (head-to-tail) or C=C dimerization.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] One decomposition pathway results in an unusual tricyclic phosphine which can be selectively formed by irradiating a solution of the phosphaallene, iBu2AlH, and TripP(C≡CtBu)2 in n-hexanes for 60h with a mercury vapor lamp.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Under these conditions, the tricyclic phosphine was isolated in high yield and a purity of >95%.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Recently, two novel 1-benzodihydrophosphetes were synthesized by heating 3H-phosphaallene Mes*P=C=C(H)R (R = tBu, Ad) in toluene at 110 °C for 16-20h.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The resulting 1- benzodihydrophosphetes were not stable unless coordinated to tungsten.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The phosphorus-bound H of the product can be used in catalyst-free hydrophosphination reactions and in the synthesis of bulky phosphine ligands.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration is used as a method to reduce unsaturated compounds, and has been used to reduce P-C double or triple bonds in phosphaalkenes and phosphaalkynes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration of the 3H-phosphaallene Mes*-P=C=C(H)-tBu with 1:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded a di(phosphaalkenyl)borane, and the reaction in 2:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded the desired product with a B atom bound to two P=C double bonds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroboration of the C=C bond was preferred over the hydroboration of the P=C bond.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes are typically colorless or pale yellow in color, and are often crystalline in structure; however, few crystal structures have been reported for this class of compounds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] One compound, ArP=C=CPh2 (Ar =Mes*) was synthesized and characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] This compound showed a relatively short P=C double bond length of 1.625(4)Å and a short C=C bond length of 1.1327(5)Å, which closely resembles the bond length in an allene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure also showed a bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle at 168.0(3)°.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] This bent geometry is thought to be a result of both steric and electronic effects.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] One possible explanation for the observed bent geometry is the bonding model postulated by Lappert et al. which described the bonding between P and the C as singlet states that act in a double π-donor-acceptor fashion.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure of another 1-phosphaallene RP=C=CHR' (R= Mes*, R' = tBu) displays the same bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle being reported as 170.7°.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] Further, this compound also contains a short P=C bond length (1.634Å) and a short C=C bond length (1.136Å).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The electronic structure of 1-phosphaallene is nearly identical to that of phosphaalkene.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The HOMO in both molecules is the π-orbital of the C=P bond, which is primarily P in character.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The LUMO in both structures, is also heavily localized over the C=P bond.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] However, the dipole moment in phosphaallenes is larger than that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In compounds with the antisymmetric form X=C=Y, IR stretching bands are observed in the 1600–2300 cm−1 region.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] However, the IR spectra of 1-phosphaallenes do not contain bands in this region, which suggests that the phosphaallene P=C=C is relatively symmetric.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In the phosphaallene H2C=C=PH, stretching frequencies are observed at 1788 and 789 cm−1, which are attributed to the C=C bond and the C=P bond, respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] In similar compounds containing a C=C=N skeleton, there is a very strong band present within the 1600 – 2300 cm−1 region.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/1-phosphaallenes] The presence of two stretching frequencies rather than one strong frequency in the phosphaallene supports that the C=C and C=P bonds are nearly independent of one another electronically.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] In organic chemistry, an **acetal** is a functional group with the connectivity R2C(OR')2.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Here, the R groups can be organic fragments (a carbon atom, with arbitrary other atoms attached to that) or hydrogen, while the R' groups must be organic fragments, not hydrogen.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The two R' groups can be equivalent to each other (a "symmetric acetal") or not (a "mixed acetal").
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] An acetal is formed from and convertible to two alcohol molecules and an aldehyde or ketone, but acetals have substantially different chemical stability and reactivity as compared to the analogous carbonyl compounds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The central carbon atom has four bonds to it, and is therefore saturated and has tetrahedral geometry.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The IUPAC originally deprecated the usage of the word ketal altogether, but has since reversed its decision.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] However, in contrast to historical usage, ketals are now a subset of acetals, a term that now encompasses both aldehyde- and ketone-derived structures.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] If one of the R groups has an oxygen as the first atom (that is, there are more than two oxygens single-bonded to the central carbon), the functional group is instead an orthoester.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] In contrast to variations of R, both R' groups are organic fragments.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] If one R' is a hydrogen, the functional group is instead a hemiacetal, while if both are H, the functional group is a ketone hydrate or aldehyde hydrate.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Formation of an acetal occurs when the hydroxyl group of a hemiacetal becomes protonated and is lost as water.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The carbocation that is produced is then rapidly attacked by a molecule of alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Loss of the proton from the attached alcohol gives the acetal.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Acetals are stable compared to hemiacetals but their formation is a reversible equilibrium as with esters.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] As a reaction to create an acetal proceeds, water must be removed from the reaction mixture, for example, with a Dean–Stark apparatus, lest it hydrolyse the product back to the hemiacetal.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The formation of acetals reduces the total number of molecules present (carbonyl + 2 alcohol → acetal + water) and therefore is generally not favourable with regard to entropy.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] One situation where the reaction is not entropically unfavourable is when a single diol molecule is used rather than two separate alcohol molecules (carbonyl + diol → acetal + water).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Acetalization and ketalization are the organic reactions that involve the formation of an acetal (or ketals) from aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Since each step is often a rapid equilibrium, the reaction must be driven by removal of water.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Methods for removing water include azeotropic distillation and trapping water with desiccants like aluminium oxide and molecular sieves.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Steps assumed to be involved: protonation of the carbonyl oxygen, addition of the alcohol to the protonated carbonyl, protonolysis of the resulting hemiacetal or hemiketal, and addition of the second alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Another way to avoid the entropic cost is to perform the synthesis by acetal exchange (**transacetalization**), using a pre-existing acetal-type reagent as the OR'-group donor rather than simple addition of alcohols themselves.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] One type of reagent used for this method is an orthoester.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] In this case, water produced along with the acetal product is destroyed when it hydrolyses residual orthoester molecules, and this side reaction also produces more alcohol to be used in the main reaction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Since many sugars are polyhydroxy aldehydes and ketones, sugars are a rich source of acetals and ketals.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Most glycosidic bonds in carbohydrates and other polysaccharides are acetal linkages.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Cellulose is a ubiquitous example of a polyacetal.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Benzylidene acetal and acetonide as protecting groups used in research of modified sugars.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Acetals also find application as chiral auxiliaries.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Indeed acetals of chiral glycols like, e.g. derivatives of tartaric acid can be asymmetrically opened with high selectivity.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] This enables the construction of new chiral centers.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Formaldehyde forms a rich collection of acetals.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] This tendency reflects the fact that low molecular weight aldehydes are prone to self-condensation such that the C=O bond is replaced by an acetal.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The acetal formed from formaldehyde (two hydrogens attached to the central carbon) is sometimes called a *formal* or the methylenedioxy group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] The acetal formed from acetone is sometimes called an acetonide.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Formaldehyde forms paraformaldehyde and 1,3,5-trioxane.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Polyoxymethylene (POM) plastic, also known as "acetal" or "polyacetal", is a polyacetal (and a polyether), and a polymer of formaldehyde.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Acetaldehyde converts to paraldehyde and metaldehyde.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Phenylsulfonylethylidene (PSE) acetal is an example of arylsulfonyl acetal possessing atypical properties, like resistance to acid hydrolysis which leads to selective introduction and removal of the protective group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] 1,1-Diethoxyethane (acetaldehyde diethyl acetal), sometimes called simply "acetal", is an important flavouring compound in distilled beverages.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Two ketals of ethyl acetoacetate are used in commercial fragrances.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Fructone (CH3C(O2C2H4)CH2CO2C2H5), an ethylene glycol ketal, and fraistone (CH3C(O2C2H3CH3)CH2CO2C2H5), a propylene glycol ketal, are commercial fragrances.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] Used in a more general sense, the term **X**,**Y**-*acetal* also refers to any functional group that consists of a carbon bearing two heteroatoms **X** and **Y**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetal] For example, *N*,*O*-acetal refers to compounds of type R1R2C(OR)(NR'2) (R,R' ≠ H) also known as a *hemiaminal ether* or aminal, a.k.a. aminoacetal.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] In organic chemistry, the **acetoxy group** (abbr.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] **AcO–** or **–OAc**; IUPAC name: **acetyloxy**), is a functional group with the formula −OCOCH3 and the structure −O−C(=O)−CH3.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] As the *-oxy* suffix implies, it differs from the acetyl group (−C(=O)−CH3) by the presence of an additional oxygen atom.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] The name acetoxy is the short form of *acetyl-oxy*.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] An acetoxy group may be used as a protection for an alcohol functionality in a synthetic route although the protecting group itself is called an acetyl group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetoxy-group] An alcohol is not a particularly strong nucleophile and, when present, more powerful nucleophiles like amines will react with the above-mentioned reagents in preference to the alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] In organic chemistry, an **acetyl group** is a functional group denoted by the chemical formula −COCH3 and the structure −C(=O)−CH3.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] It is sometimes represented by the symbol **Ac** (not to be confused with the element actinium).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] In IUPAC nomenclature, an acetyl group is called an **ethanoyl** **group**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] An acetyl group contains a methyl group (−CH3) that is single-bonded to a carbonyl (C=O), making it an acyl group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] The acetyl moiety is a component of many organic compounds, including acetic acid, the neurotransmitter acetylcholine, acetyl-CoA, acetylcysteine, acetaminophen (also known as paracetamol), and acetylsalicylic acid (also known as aspirin).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetylation is the chemical reaction known as "ethanoylation" in the IUPAC nomenclature.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] It depicts a reactionary process that injects an acetyl functional group into a chemical compound.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] The opposite reaction is called "**de**acetylation", and this is the **removal** of the acetyl group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Enzymes which perform acetylation on proteins or other biomolecules are known as acetyltransferases.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] In biological organisms, acetyl groups are commonly transferred from acetyl-CoA to other organic molecules.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetyl-CoA is an intermediate in the biological synthesis and in the breakdown of many organic molecules.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetyl-CoA is also created during the second stage of cellular respiration (pyruvate decarboxylation) by the action of pyruvate dehydrogenase on pyruvic acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Proteins are often modified via acetylation, for various purposes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] For example, acetylation of histones by histone acetyltransferases (HATs) results in an expansion of local chromatin structure, allowing transcription to occur by enabling RNA polymerase to access DNA.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] However, removal of the acetyl group by histone deacetylases (HDACs) condenses the local chromatin structure, thereby preventing transcription.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetylation can be achieved by chemists using a variety of methods, most commonly with the use of acetic anhydride or acetyl chloride, often in the presence of a tertiary or aromatic amine base.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] The amine base is primarily used to capture free protons, but may also further activate the acetyl group towards nucleophilic attack.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetylated organic molecules exhibit increased ability to cross the selectively permeable blood–brain barrier.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetylation helps a given drug reach the brain more quickly, making the drug's effects more intense and increasing the effectiveness of a given dose.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] The acetyl group in acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin) enhances its effectiveness relative to the natural anti-inflammatant salicylic acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] In similar manner, acetylation converts the natural painkiller morphine into the far more potent heroin (diacetylmorphine).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] There is some evidence that acetyl-L-carnitine may be more effective for some applications than L-carnitine.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] Acetylation of resveratrol holds promise as one of the first anti-radiation medicines for human populations.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] The term "acetyl" was coined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1839 to describe what is now known as the vinyl group (coined in 1851).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acetyl-group] "Acetyl" is derived from the Latin *acētum,* meaning "vinegar.", and the Greek *Húlē,* meaning substance, or material.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated carbonyl compounds can be subclassified according to the nature of the carbonyl and alkene groups.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated carbonyl compounds featuring a carbonyl conjugated to an alkene that is terminal, or vinylic, contain the **acryloyl group** (H2C=CH−C(=O)−); it is the acyl group derived from acrylic acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The preferred IUPAC name for the group is **prop-2-enoyl**, and it is also known as **acrylyl** or simply (and incorrectly) as **acryl**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Compounds containing an acryloyl group can be referred to as "acrylic compounds".
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] An **α,β-unsaturated acid** is a type of α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compound that consists of an alkene conjugated to a carboxylic acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The simplest example is acrylic acid (CH2=CHCO2H).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] These compounds are prone to polymerization, giving rise to the large area of polyacrylate plastics.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Acrylate polymers are derived from but do not contain the acrylate group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The carboxyl group of acrylic acid can react with ammonia to form acrylamide, or with an alcohol to form an acrylate ester.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Acrylamide and methyl acrylate are commercially important examples of α,β-unsaturated amides and α,β-unsaturated esters, respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Acrylic acid, its esters, and its amide derivatives feature the acryloyl group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated dicarbonyls are also common.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The parent compounds are maleic acid and the isomeric fumaric acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Maleic acid forms esters, an imide, and an anhydride, i.e. diethyl maleate, maleimide, and maleic anhydride.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Fumaric acid, as fumarate, is an intermediate in the Krebs citric acid cycle, which is of great importance in bioenergy.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] An **enone** (or **alkenone**) is an organic compound containing both alkene and ketone functional groups.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] In an α,β-unsaturated enone, the alkene is conjugated to the carbonyl group of the ketone.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The simplest enone is methyl vinyl ketone (butenone, CH2=CHCOCH3).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Enones are typically produced through an aldol or Knoevenagel condensation, both in industry and in the laboratory.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Some commercially significant enones produced by condensations of acetone are mesityl oxide (dimer of acetone) and phorone and isophorone (trimers of the same).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Certain specialized enolic oxidations also form enones.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The selenoxide elimination and Saegusa-Ito oxidation both effect a leaving group near the ketone that spontaneously eliminates.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] When N-tert-butyl benzenesulfinimidoyl chloride or IBX oxidize an enolate, the result is 1,4-elimination.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Finally, the Meyer–Schuster rearrangement converts a propargylic alcohol to an enone with acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The cyclic enones include cyclopropenone, cyclobutenone, cyclopentenone, cyclohexenone, and cycloheptenone.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Cyclopentenones can be prepared via the Pauson–Khand reaction or Nazarov cyclization.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] An **enal** (or **alkenal**) is an organic compound containing both alkene and aldehyde functional groups.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] In an α,β-unsaturated enal, the alkene is conjugated to the carbonyl group of the aldehyde (formyl group).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The simplest enal is acrolein (CH2=CHCHO).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Other examples include *cis*-3-hexenal (essence of mowed lawns) and cinnamaldehyde (essence of cinnamon).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated carbonyls are electrophilic at both the carbonyl carbon as well as the β-carbon.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Depending on conditions, either site is attacked by nucleophiles.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Additions to the alkene are called conjugate additions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] One type of conjugate addition is the Michael addition, which is used commercially in the conversion of mesityl oxide into isophorone.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Owing to their extended conjugation, α,β-unsaturated carbonyls are prone to polymerization.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] In terms of industrial scale, polymerization dominates the use of α,β-unsaturated carbonyls.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Again because of their electrophilic character, the alkene portion of α,β-unsaturated carbonyls is good dienophiles in Diels–Alder reactions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] They can be further activated by Lewis acids, which bind to the carbonyl oxygen. α,β-Unsaturated carbonyls are good ligands for low-valent metal complexes, examples being (bda)Fe(CO)3 and tris(dibenzylideneacetone)dipalladium(0).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated carbonyls are readily hydrogenated.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Hydrogenation can target the carbonyl or the alkene (conjugate reduction) selectively, or both functional groups.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Enones undergo the Nazarov cyclization reaction and in the Rauhut–Currier reaction (dimerization).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] When appropriately irradiated, they undergo enone–alkene cycloadditions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Similar to vinyl ethers, α,β-unsaturated carbonyls initially metallate at the β (electrophilic) position, before relaxing to α metallation.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] α,β-Unsaturated thioesters are intermediates in several enzymatic processes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Two prominent examples are coumaroyl-coenzyme A and crotonyl-coenzyme A.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] They arise by the action of acyl-CoA dehydrogenases.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) is a required co-factor.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Since α,β-unsaturated compounds are electrophiles and alkylating agents, many α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds are toxic.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] The endogenous scavenger compound glutathione naturally protects from toxic electrophiles in the body.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acryloyl-group] Some drugs (amifostine, *N*-acetylcysteine) containing thiol groups may protect from such harmful alkylation.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] In organic chemistry, an **acyl chloride** (or **acid chloride**) is an organic compound with the functional group −C(=O)Cl.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Their formula is usually written R−COCl, where R is a side chain.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] They are reactive derivatives of carboxylic acids (R−C(=O)OH).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] A specific example of an acyl chloride is acetyl chloride, CH3COCl.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chlorides are the most important subset of acyl halides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Where the acyl chloride moiety takes priority, acyl chlorides are named by taking the name of the parent carboxylic acid, and substituting *-yl chloride* for *-ic acid*.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chlorides of dicarboxylic acids, called diacyl chlorides (sometimes diacid chlorides or dioyl chlorides), follow similar rules, retaining either their common name or a multiplicative prefix before **-yl** and **chloride**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Lacking the ability to form hydrogen bonds, acyl chlorides have lower boiling and melting points than similar carboxylic acids.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] For example, acetic acid boils at 118 °C, whereas acetyl chloride boils at 51 °C.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Like most carbonyl compounds, infrared spectroscopy reveals a band near 1750 cm−1.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The simplest stable acyl chloride is acetyl chloride; formyl chloride is not stable at room temperature, although it can be prepared at −60 °C or below.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Similarly, benzotrichlorides react with carboxylic acids to the acid chloride.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] In the laboratory, acyl chlorides are generally prepared by treating carboxylic acids with thionyl chloride (SOCl2).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The reaction is catalyzed by dimethylformamide and other additives.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Thionyl chloride⁠ is a well-suited reagent as the by-products (HCl, SO2) are gases and residual thionyl chloride can be easily removed as a result of its low boiling point (76 °C).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Phosphorus trichloride (PCl3) is popular, although excess reagent is required.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The reaction is catalysed by dimethylformamide (DMF), which reacts with oxalyl chloride to give the Vilsmeier reagent, an iminium intermediate that which reacts with the carboxylic acid to form a mixed imino-anhydride.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] This structure undergoes an acyl substitution with the liberated chloride, forming the acid anhydride and releasing regenerated molecule of DMF.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Relative to thionyl chloride, oxalyl chloride is more expensive but also a milder reagent and therefore more selective.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid chlorides can be used as a chloride source.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chloride are reactive, versatile reagents.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] This hydrolysis is usually a nuisance rather than intentional.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid chlorides are useful for the preparation of amides, esters, anhydrides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] These reactions generate chloride, which can be undesirable.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chlorides are used to prepare acid anhydrides, amides and esters, by reacting acid chlorides with: a salt of a carboxylic acid, an amine, or an alcohol, respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid halides are the most reactive acyl derivatives, and can easily be converted into any of the others.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid halides will react with carboxylic acids to form anhydrides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] If the structure of the acid and the acid chloride are different, the product is a mixed anhydride.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] First, the carboxylic acid attacks the acid chloride (**1**) to give tetrahedral intermediate **2**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The tetrahedral intermediate collapses, ejecting chloride ion as the leaving group and forming oxonium species **3**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Deprotonation gives the mixed anhydride, **4**, and an equivalent of HCl.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Alcohols and amines react with acid halides to produce esters and amides, respectively, in a reaction formally known as the Schotten-Baumann reaction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid halides hydrolyze in the presence of water to produce carboxylic acids, but this type of reaction is rarely useful, since carboxylic acids are typically used to synthesize acid halides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Most reactions with acid halides are carried out in the presence of a non-nucleophilic base, such as pyridine, to neutralize the hydrohalic acid that is formed as a byproduct.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Bases, such as pyridine or *N,N*-dimethylformamide, catalyze acylations.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] These reagents activate the acyl chloride via a nucleophilic catalysis mechanism.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The amine attacks the carbonyl bond and presumably⁠ first forms a transient tetrahedral intermediate, then forms a quaternary acylammonium salt by the displacement of the leaving group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] This quaternary acylammonium salt is more susceptible to attack by alcohols or other nucleophiles.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The use of two phases (aqueous for amine, organic for acyl chloride) is called the Schotten-Baumann reaction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acid halides react with carbon nucleophiles, such as Grignards and enolates, although mixtures of products can result.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] While a carbon nucleophile will react with the acid halide first to produce a ketone, the ketone is also susceptible to nucleophilic attack, and can be converted to a tertiary alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] For example, when benzoyl chloride (**1**) is treated with two equivalents of a Grignard reagent, such as methyl magnesium bromide (MeMgBr), 2-phenyl-2-propanol (**3**) is obtained in excellent yield.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Although acetophenone (**2**) is an intermediate in this reaction, it is impossible to isolate because it reacts with a second equivalent of MeMgBr rapidly after being formed.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] (Benzoyl reacts with an excess of methylmagnesium Grignard to form a tertiary alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Unlike most other carbon nucleophiles, lithium dialkylcuprates – often called Gilman reagents – can add to acid halides just once to give ketones.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The reaction between an acid halide and a Gilman reagent is not a nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction, however, and is thought to proceed via a radical pathway.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The Weinreb ketone synthesis can also be used to convert acid halides to ketones.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] In this reaction, the acid halide is first converted to an N–methoxy–N–methylamide, known as a Weinreb amide.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] When a carbon nucleophile – such as a Grignard or organolithium reagent – adds to a Weinreb amide, the metal is chelated by the carbonyl and N–methoxy oxygens, preventing further nucleophilic additions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Carbon nucleophiles such as Grignard reagents, convert acyl chlorides to ketones, which in turn are susceptible to the attack by second equivalent to yield the tertiary alcohol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The reaction of acyl halides with certain organocadmium reagents stops at the ketone stage.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] The reaction with Gilman reagents also afford ketones, reflecting the low nucleophilicity of these lithium diorganocopper compounds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chlorides are reduced by lithium aluminium hydride and diisobutylaluminium hydride to give primary alcohols.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Lithium tri-tert-butoxyaluminium hydride, a bulky hydride donor, reduces acyl chlorides to aldehydes, as does the Rosenmund reduction using hydrogen gas over a poisoned palladium catalyst.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] In the Friedel–Crafts acylation, acid halides act as electrophiles for electrophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] A Lewis acid – such as zinc chloride (ZnCl2), iron(III) chloride (FeCl3), or aluminum chloride (AlCl3) – coordinates to the halogen on the acid halide, activating the compound towards nucleophilic attack by an activated aromatic ring.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] For especially electron-rich aromatic rings, the reaction will proceed without a Lewis acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Because of the harsh conditions and the reactivity of the intermediates, this otherwise quite useful reaction tends to be messy, as well as environmentally unfriendly.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Acyl chlorides react with low-valent metal centers to give transition metal acyl complexes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-chloride] Low molecular weight acyl chlorides are often lachrymators, and they react violently with water, alcohols, and amines.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In chemistry, an **acyl group** is a moiety derived by the removal of one or more hydroxyl groups from an oxoacid, including inorganic acids.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] It contains a double-bonded oxygen atom and an organyl group (R−C=O) or hydrogen in the case of formyl group (H−C=O).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In organic chemistry, the acyl group (IUPAC name **alkanoyl** if the organyl group is alkyl) is usually derived from a carboxylic acid, in which case it has the formula R−C(=O)−, where R represents an organyl group or hydrogen.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Although the term is almost always applied to organic compounds, acyl groups can in principle be derived from other types of acids such as sulfonic acids and phosphonic acids.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In the most common arrangement, acyl groups are attached to a larger molecular fragment, in which case the carbon and oxygen atoms are linked by a double bond.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] There are five main types of acyl derivatives.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acid halides are the most reactive towards nucleophiles, followed by anhydrides, esters, and amides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Carboxylate ions are essentially unreactive towards nucleophilic substitution, since they possess no leaving group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The reactivity of these five classes of compounds covers a broad range; the relative reaction rates of acid chlorides and amides differ by a factor of 1013.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] A major factor in determining the reactivity of acyl derivatives is leaving group ability, which is related to acidity.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Weak bases are better leaving groups than strong bases; a species with a strong conjugate acid (e.g. hydrochloric acid) will be a better leaving group than a species with a weak conjugate acid (e.g. acetic acid).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Thus, chloride ion is a better leaving group than acetate ion.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The reactivity of acyl compounds towards nucleophiles decreases as the basicity of the leaving group increases, as the table shows.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Another factor that plays a role in determining the reactivity of acyl compounds is resonance.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Amides exhibit two main resonance forms.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Both are major contributors to the overall structure, so much so that the amide bond between the carbonyl carbon and the amide nitrogen has significant double bond character.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The energy barrier for rotation about an amide bond is 75–85 kJ/mol (18–20 kcal/mol), much larger than values observed for normal single bonds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] For example, the C–C bond in ethane has an energy barrier of only 12 kJ/mol (3 kcal/mol).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Once a nucleophile attacks and a tetrahedral intermediate is formed, the energetically favorable resonance effect is lost.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] This helps explain why amides are one of the least reactive acyl derivatives.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Esters exhibit less resonance stabilization than amides, so the formation of a tetrahedral intermediate and subsequent loss of resonance is not as energetically unfavorable.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Anhydrides experience even weaker resonance stabilization, since the resonance is split between two carbonyl groups, and are more reactive than esters and amides.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In acid halides, there is very little resonance, so the energetic penalty for forming a tetrahedral intermediate is small.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] This helps explain why acid halides are the most reactive acyl derivatives.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Well-known acyl compounds are the acyl chlorides, such as acetyl chloride (CH3COCl) and benzoyl chloride (C6H5COCl).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] These compounds, which are treated as sources of acylium cations, are good reagents for attaching acyl groups to various substrates.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Amides (**RC(O)**NR′2) and esters (**RC(O)**OR′) are classes of acyl compounds, as are ketones (**RC(O)**R′) and aldehydes (**RC(O)**H), where R and R′ stand for organyl (or hydrogen in the case of formyl).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acylium ions are cations of the formula RCO+.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The carbon–oxygen bond length in these cations is near 1.1 Å (110-112 pm), which is shorter than the 112.8 pm of carbon monoxide and indicates triple-bond character.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The carbon centres of acylium ions generally have a linear geometry and sp atomic hybridization, and are best represented by a resonance structure bearing a formal positive charge on the oxygen (rather than carbon): [R−C≡O+].
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] They are characteristic fragments observed in EI-mass spectra of ketones.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acylium ions are common reactive intermediates, for example in the Friedel–Crafts acylation and many other organic reactions such as the Hayashi rearrangement.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acyl radicals are commonly generated when thiyl or other, more electrophilic radicals abstract hydrogen atoms from aldehydes (alkyl radicals do so very inefficiently).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acyl anions are almost always unstable—usually too unstable to be exploited synthetically.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] They readily react with the neutral aldehyde to form an acyloin dimer.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Hence, synthetic chemists have developed various acyl anion synthetic equivalents, such as dithianes, as surrogates.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] However, as a partial exception, hindered dialkylformamides (e.g., diisopropylformamide, HCON*i*Pr2) can undergo deprotonation at low temperature (−78 °C) with lithium diisopropylamide as the base to form a carbamoyl anion stable at these temperatures.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In biochemistry there are many instances of acyl groups, in all major categories of biochemical molecules.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acyl-CoAs are acyl derivatives formed via fatty acid metabolism.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acetyl-CoA, the most common derivative, serves as an acyl donor in many biosynthetic transformations.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Names of acyl groups of amino acids are formed by replacing the *-ine* suffix with *-yl*.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] For example, the acyl group of glycine is glycyl, and of lysine is lysyl.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Names of acyl groups of ribonucleoside monophosphates such as AMP (5′-adenylic acid), GMP (5′-guanylic acid), CMP (5′-cytidylic acid), and UMP (5′-uridylic acid) are adenylyl, guanylyl, cytidylyl, and uridylyl respectively.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In phospholipids, the acyl group of phosphatidic acid is called phosphatidyl-.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acyl ligands are intermediates in many carbonylation reactions, which are important in some catalytic reactions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Metal acyls arise usually via insertion of carbon monoxide into metal–alkyl bonds.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Metal acyls also arise from reactions involving acyl chlorides with low-valence metal complexes or by the reaction of organolithium compounds with metal carbonyls.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Metal acyls are often described by two resonance structures, one of which emphasizes the basicity of the oxygen center.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] *O*-alkylation of metal acyls gives Fischer carbene complexes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The common names of acyl groups are derived typically by replacing the **-ic acid** suffix of the corresponding carboxylic acid's common name with **-yl** (or **-oyl**), as shown in the table below.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The acyls are between the hydrocarbyls and the carboxylic acids.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The hydrocarbyl group names that end in -yl are not acyl groups, but alkyl groups derived from alkanes (methyl, ethyl, propyl, butyl), alkenyl groups derived from alkenes (propenyl, butenyl), or aryl groups (benzyl).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acyl compounds react with nucleophiles via an addition mechanism: the nucleophile attacks the carbonyl carbon, forming a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] This reaction can be accelerated by acidic conditions, which make the carbonyl more electrophilic, or basic conditions, which provide a more anionic and therefore more reactive nucleophile.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The tetrahedral intermediate itself can be an alcohol or alkoxide, depending on the pH of the reaction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The tetrahedral intermediate of an acyl compound contains a substituent attached to the central carbon that can act as a leaving group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] After the tetrahedral intermediate forms, it collapses, recreating the carbonyl C=O bond and ejecting the leaving group in an elimination reaction.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] As a result of this two-step addition/elimination process, the nucleophile takes the place of the leaving group on the carbonyl compound by way of an intermediate state that does not contain a carbonyl.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Both steps are reversible and as a result, nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions are equilibrium processes.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Because the equilibrium will favor the product containing the best nucleophile, the leaving group must be a comparatively poor nucleophile in order for a reaction to be practical.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Under acidic conditions, the carbonyl group of the acyl compound **1** is protonated, which activates it towards nucleophilic attack.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In the second step, the protonated carbonyl **2** is attacked by a nucleophile (H−Z) to give tetrahedral intermediate **3**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Proton transfer from the nucleophile (Z) to the leaving group (X) gives **4**, which then collapses to eject the protonated leaving group (H−X), giving protonated carbonyl compound **5**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The loss of a proton gives the substitution product, **6**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Because the last step involves the loss of a proton, nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions are considered catalytic in acid.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Also note that under acidic conditions, a nucleophile will typically exist in its protonated form (i.e.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Under basic conditions, a nucleophile (Nuc) attacks the carbonyl group of the acyl compound **1** to give tetrahedral alkoxide intermediate **2**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] The intermediate collapses and expels the leaving group (X) to give the substitution product **3**.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] While nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions can be base-catalyzed, the reaction will not occur if the leaving group is a stronger base than the nucleophile (i.e. the leaving group must have a lower p*K*a than the nucleophile).
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Unlike acid-catalyzed processes, both the nucleophile and the leaving group exist as anions under basic conditions.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] This mechanism is supported by isotope labeling experiments.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] When ethyl propionate with an oxygen-18-labeled ethoxy group is treated with sodium hydroxide (NaOH), the oxygen-18 label is completely absent from propionic acid and is found exclusively in the ethanol.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] In **acyloxy** groups the acyl group is bonded to oxygen: R−C(=O)−O−R′ where R−C(=O) is the acyl group.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] Acylium ions are cations of the formula R−C≡O+.
[src:1-phosphaallenes/acyl-group] They are intermediates in Friedel-Crafts acylations.
